hay</i> is found mainly among African Americans."],"variants":[{"name":"Gosha","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Angelle, Mechelle, Monique.","Americanized form of French   Gauthier  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Gosche  ."]}]},{"name":"Gottfried","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>god</i>, <i>got</i> ‘god’ + <i>frid</i> ‘peace’; borne by the 13th-century poet Gottfried von Strassburg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified spelling of   John   or a short form of   Jonathan .  The name is borne by the Canadian singer  Jon Vickers  (  b. 1926 ) and the American actor  Jon Voight  (  b. 1938 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jonathan","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘God has given’, composed of the same elements as those of   Matthew  , but in reverse order. This is the name of several characters in the Bible, most notably a son of King Saul, who was a devoted friend and supporter of the young David, even when David and Saul were themselves at loggerheads (1 Samuel 31; 2 Samuel 1:19–26). The name is often taken as symbolic of steadfast friendship and loyalty. Well-known bearers of the name include the Irish clergyman and writer  Jonathan Swift  (  1667-1745 ), British theatre director  Jonathan Miller  (  b. 1934 ), British actor  Jonathan Pryce  (  b. 1947 ), and British television presenter  Jonathan Ross  (  b. 1960 )."]},{"name":"Jonn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jon   or  <b>John</b> ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gottfried l. von Gosham was born about 1070 as the son of Ulrich von Gosham and Mrs. Mrs. Ulrich. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Mrs. Gottfreid. He died in 1143, in Holy Roman Empire, at the age of